Aet IV. Sed. A second time is Charmides checked on the threshold of his house by the approach of Stasimus, who, being in great trouble about Lesbonicus, has added one more to his misfortunes by losing his ring at a wine shop. The master amuses himself for a few minutes with the half-drunken platitudes of his slave before Stasimus is aware of his presence. Then all the bad news comes upon him at once.

The reeklessness of his son, the ruin of his property, the sale of his house, the supposed treachery of his friend—all these calamities overcome him and he well nigh faints away.

Aet IV. So. 4. The loud voices in the street bring out Callicles spade in hand, from digging up the treasure. Char- mides is quickly reassured and praises his friend's fidelity.
